main event: On June 2, 1952, in Eatontown, New Jersey, a ground radar observed a single object for a duration of two minutes, but wind information suggests the object would move very slowly. The conclusion was that it was probably a balloon, possibly an aircraft.
interesting points: The object was observed for two minutes, but the wind information indicated slow movement.
The conclusion was that it was probably a balloon, possibly an aircraft, based on radar observations.
One report suggested the sighting was possibly caused by a helicopter due to the shape and size of the object.
Another report described the object as bright red and vapor-like, visible for several seconds, with insufficient data for evaluation of its course.
There were observations of an elongated object emitting slight vapor, with a negative analysis on its nature and origin.
sighted object: single object observed via ground radar
photographs: no photographs included in the report
